  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real, tangible thing that affects how people approach science and engineering. Growing up in Kansas City as an immigrant with parents who didn't finish high school, I've seen firsthand how expectations can shape a person's confidence. When someone believes they're part of a group that's historically underrepresented in tech fields, their performance can suffer not because they lack ability, but because of the stress of that stereotype. For example, I remember a time when I was fixing a circuit and a student from my workshop asked me if I thought they could do it too. I didn't want to discourage them, but I also knew the fear of being labeled 'not smart enough' could hold them back. This isn't just about girls or minorities—it's about anyone who feels their identity might clash with the field they're trying to enter. Addressing stereotype threat requires changing the way we talk about STEM, not just in classrooms but in real-life settings like workshops and community centers. It means creating environments where people feel safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. As a creative problem-solver who's spent years working with hands-on tools, I've learned that confidence comes from practical experience and community support. We need to build those spaces where everyone feels they belong, whether they're fixing a car or building a circuit. It's not about changing the field itself but about making sure everyone has the opportunity to contribute without the weight of stereotypes holding them back.",
